<a name=3D"overview">
</a></p><h2><a name=3D"overview">Project Overview</a></h2><a name=3D"overvi=
ew">
<p>
</p></a><dir><a name=3D"overview"></a><dir><a name=3D"overview">
This SSNwatch project has four primary goals related to Social Security num=
bers (SSNs).
These are described below.
<p>
</p><dir>
<ol>
<li>Matching people and SSNs
</li><li>Measuring the identifiability of SSNs, in whole and part
</li><li>Assessing the public availability of SSNs
</li><li>Proposing and reviewing technical and policy solutions
</li></ol>
</dir>
<p>
</p></a><ol><a name=3D"overview">
</a><li><a name=3D"overview"><h3>Matching People and SSNs</h3>
</a><p><a name=3D"overview">
A goal of the SSNwatch project, presented here,
is to explore how publicly available information about=20
people and about Social Security numbers (SSNs) can be used to verify=20
whether a given SSN matches the person presenting the SSN, and vice versa.
By identifying the state in which the SSN was issued,=20
the date the SSN was issued, the estimated age range of the recipient,=20
and whether the number has been retired from use,=20
we can provide inferences about the person presenting the SSN.
This information can then be matched against other information=20
the person provides for consistency.
Mismatches in this information can help identify suspicious=20
presentations of SSNs. Perhaps imposters might be exposed.
The </a><a href=3D"https://dataprivacylab.org/dataprivacy/projects/ssnwatch=
/index.html">SSNwatch Validation Service</a>=20
available above provides such information.
In future work, we will also provide inferences in the opposite direction,
thereby relating information known about a person to what must be true abou=
t their SSN.
</p><p>
We envision our=20
<a href=3D"https://dataprivacylab.org/dataprivacy/projects/ssnwatch/index.h=
tml">SSNwatch Validation Service</a>=20
as a way to help combat
<a href=3D"https://dataprivacylab.org/dataprivacy/projects/ssnwatch/identit=
ytheft.html">Identity theft</a>.
In the United States, SSNs are essential to recognizing=20
the identity of a person in data. SSNs associate people with various types =
of health, financial, legal, educational, and billing information.=20
It is not surprising therefore, that SSNs are an essential ingredient to mo=
st
forms of identity theft. Being able to verify that the person presenting an
SSN is the person to whom the SSN was assigned may be useful in recognizing=
 false identities presented by employees, tenants, students, and others.
</p><p>
<br>
</p></li><li><h3>Measuring the Identifiability of SSNs</h3>
<p>
Another goal of this SSNwatch project is to determine the identifiability
of an SSN in whole or part. =20
Some people believe that releasing only an SSN, in part or whole,
cannot be readily re-identified to the person to whom the SSN was issued
without access to credit reports
or other information containing both the person's SSN and name explicitly. =
=20
Such a belief may pose=20
<a href=3D"https://dataprivacylab.org/dataprivacy/projects/ssnwatch/privacy=
.html">privacy</a>
risks for those who's SSNs are released.
To demonstrate whether this is merely a myth, we begin by understanding
how much and what kind of information is revealed about a person=20
when part or all of the person's SSN is shared. The data within the=20
<a href=3D"https://dataprivacylab.org/dataprivacy/projects/ssnwatch/index.h=
tml">SSNwatch Validation Service</a>=20
provides the basis for such an assessment.
</p><p>
<br>
</p></li><li><h3>Assessing the Public Availability of SSNs</h3>
<p>
A third goal of this SSNwatch project is to assess the public availability =
of SSNs,
along with related risks.  The use of SSNs is clearly widespread.=20
Some people argue that SSNs, while available within many=20
financial, health, employment, and government institutions, is still limite=
d.
The claim is that SSNs are not generally available to the public.  Recent n=
ews
reports have surfaced relating the ease at which the SSNs of known people
can be purchased for less than $30 each.  Our goal in this work=20
is to estimate how active SSNs can be obtained for free and to examine
the availability of these SSNs for identity theft and the acquisition=20
of fraudulent credit cards.=20
</p><p>
<br>
</p></li><li><h3>Developing and Proposing Technical and Policy Solutions</h=
3>
<p>
Another goal of this SSNwatch project is to provide technical integrations,
add-ons and stand-alone technology that render uses of SSNs more socially r=
esponsible,=20
and to provide policy and legal analyses that examine the effectiveness of =
these technologies, and to recommend policy accordingly.=20
</p></li></ol>
<p>
The SSNwatch project is part of our Surveillance of Surveillances=20
(<a href=3D"https://dataprivacylab.org/dataprivacy/projects/sos/index.html"=
>SOS</a>) effort.=20
</p><p>
</p></dir></dir>
